**Motivation and Context**

Currently only SoftmaxGrad and LogSoftmaxGrad exist upto version 12 although the forward operator Softmax and LogSoftmax support version 13. The gradient operators need to be modified or new gradients need to created to support training using version 13.

title: Use FusedMatMul When Transpose is Between First Dim and Contiguous Batch Dims

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
Current FusedMatMul can support only Transpose on last 2 dims. When the 2-D arrays for MatMul is the 1st and last dims, and the batch dims are contiguous in the original tensor, we can also use GemmStridedBatched to calculate without doing the Transpose. The perm pattern in the Transpose is like [1,2,0,3] or [1,2,3,0]. This PR is to support these cases using FusedMatMul.

For perf comparison using a module with Add+EinSum("ks,ksm->sm")+MSELOss, K = 16, S = 7840, M = 2048, before the changes, it's ~7ms for each step, after the changes, it's ~4.5ms for each step, which has similar perf as PyTorch.

Using ULR-XL (16 layers) for perf test, before the changes, the execution graph has 195 Transpose nodes, 16 MatMul nodes and 306 FusedMatMul nodes. After the changes the numbers are: 131 Transpose nodes and 322 FusedMatMul nodes. From nvvp profiling, for each step, the execution time reduces from ~913ms to ~882ms, which have ~4%. The gain is from the reduce of Transpose compute, and the new fused FusedMatMul nodes use GemmStridedBatched, which has comparible perf as original MatMul node.s

title: [Dup] Fix SAME_UPPER/SAME_LOWER (auto_pad attribute) in ConvTranspose
body:
**Description**:
Dup of https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5368/. Recreate this PR for cleaner commit log. Target it to ORT 1.10

To sync the definition of SAME_UPPER/SAME_LOWER among all operators and make it same as ONNX definition, switch the logic of SAME_UPPER and SAME_LOWER in ConvTranspose.

Definition of SAME_UPPER and SAME_LOWER should be as follows:
```
if auto_pads == 'SAME_UPPER':
  pad_head = paddings / 2  # smaller one 
  pad_tail = paddings - paddings / 2  # larger one
elif auto_pads == 'SAME_LOWER':
  pad_head = paddings - paddings / 2  # larger one
  pad_tail = paddings / 2  # smaller one
```

**Motivation and Context**
The `auto_pad` attribute, `SAME_UPPER` and `SAME_LOWER` of `ConvTranspose` is different from other operators' (pool and conv related operators) `auto_pad` attribute. The behavior of same attribute should be the same among all operators. Also, it does not meet the definition in ONNX.

- `SAME_UPPER` and `SAME_LOWER` in other operators
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/c20fcf26ebc0eeda41b6fd4e54d87623030ead91/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/nn/pool_attributes.h#L149
- ConvTranspose definition in ONNX:
https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/b2ed660d0a065b8346816f2c3a95d79ca79b88c9/onnx/defs/nn/defs.cc#L1222
- A related PR in ONNX (There is a contradiction of this in ONNX):
https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/3019

**Description**: Describe your changes.
Add support of S8S8 quantization format, with which both activation and weight are quantized in int8 format. This PR adds s8s8 implementation on ARM devices for operators: QLinearConv, QLinearMatMul, QLinearAveragePool, NhwcMaxPool, QLinearGlobalAveragePool. QGEMM is the most complex part in the change. Here are the dispatchers for quantized gemm:
|      | ARM64 with dot product           | ARM64                            | ARM32                                    |
|------|----------------------------------|----------------------------------|------------------------------------------|

title: Bad results during inference when using dynamic dimensions with the CUDA provider

labels.name: ep:CUDA
labels.description: issues related to the CUDA execution provider

body:
## **Describe the bug**

When using a model as simple as possible (Identity) during inference with ONNXRuntime, some results are incorrect when running on CUDA. I noticed that it only occurs on:
* some shapes and it seems that it needs to be a high dimensional tensor for the bug to appear
* the inference session needs to be shared across several inferences (`ort_session.run()`)

You'll find below 2 scripts to reproduce this bug:
* `reproduce_bug_onnxrt_export.py`: exports an Identity onnx model
* `reproduce_bug_onnxrt_infer.py`: takes `test_bug.onnx` and proceeds with the inference and prints when it bugs

## **Urgency**

This is very problematic since we just cannot use ONNXRuntime in production on our model since it just gives bad results. Creating a session for each inference adds a latency that we cannot afford. So I would say: pretty urgent


## **System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux, Archlinux
- ONNX Runtime versions:
    * onnxruntime-gpu == 1.8.0
    * onnxruntime-gpu == 1.9.0
    * onnxruntime-gpu on master as of 2021-11-04 with a custom wheel build from this [commit](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/ddb4c058526a0bc6f866be7c297354ed65f0fbc5)
- PyTorch version (required only if you want to export the onnx with a different partial shape): 1.10
- Python version: 3.9.0
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA version: 11.4
- cuDNN version: 8
- GPU model and memory: RTX 3090 (24GB), RTX 2070 (8GB), GTX 1070 Ti (8GB)

## **To Reproduce**
* You can download and unzip the model from here: [test_bug.onnx.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/7565254/test_bug.onnx.zip)
* If you download the ONNX Model attached, you just need to run `reproduce_bug_onnxrt_infer.py`
* If you want to try with different shapes than the problematic provided one, you can change `reproduce_bug_onnxrt_export.py` and run it. PyTorch 1.10 is required in this case.


**`reproduce_bug_onnxrt_export.py`**:
```python
import torch
from torch import nn


PARTIAL_SHAPE = (16, 7, 5, 3, 3)  # Problematic shape
# PARTIAL_SHAPE = (7, 5, 3, 3)      # No errors occurs with this shape

ONNX_OPSET_VERSION = 14
ONNX_FILEPATH = "test_bug.onnx"
INPUT_NAMES = ["input"]
OUTPUT_NAMES = ["output"]
DYNAMIC_AXES = {"input": {"seq_length": 0}}
DYNAMIC_AXES = {"input": [0]}
ONNXRT_DEVICE = "cuda"
ONNXRT_DEVICE_IDX = 1


MODEL = nn.Identity()

example_tensors = [torch.ones(1, *PARTIAL_SHAPE)]
torch.onnx.export(
    model=MODEL,
    args=example_tensors,
    f=ONNX_FILEPATH,
    input_names=INPUT_NAMES,
    output_names=OUTPUT_NAMES,
    dynamic_axes=DYNAMIC_AXES,
    operator_export_type=torch.onnx.OperatorExportTypes.ONNX,
    opset_version=ONNX_OPSET_VERSION,
    do_constant_folding=True,
    verbose=False)
```
**`reproduce_bug_onnxrt_infer.py`**:
```python
import numpy as np
import onnxruntime as ort


PARTIAL_SHAPE = (16, 7, 5, 3, 3)  # Problematic shape
# PARTIAL_SHAPE = (7, 5, 3, 3)      # No errors occurs with this shape


ONNX_OPSET_VERSION = 14
ONNX_FILEPATH = "test_bug.onnx"
INPUT_NAMES = ["input"]
OUTPUT_NAMES = ["output"]
DYNAMIC_AXES = {"input": {"seq_length": 0}}
DYNAMIC_AXES = {"input": [0]}
ONNXRT_DEVICE = "cuda"
ONNXRT_DEVICE_CUDA_IDX = 0
ONNXRT_DEVICE_IDX = 0


def create_onnxrt_session(onnx_filepath, device):
    cuda_providers = [
        ("CUDAExecutionProvider", {
            "device_id": ONNXRT_DEVICE_IDX,
            "arena_extend_strategy": "kNextPowerOfTwo",
            "gpu_mem_limit": 2 * 1024 * 1024 * 1024,
            "cudnn_conv_algo_search": "EXHAUSTIVE",
            "do_copy_in_default_stream": True,
        })
    ]
    cpu_providers = ["CPUExecutionProvider"]

    providers = cuda_providers if device == "cuda" else cpu_providers
    sess_options = ort.SessionOptions()
    sess_options.graph_optimization_level = ort.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_DISABLE_ALL
    return ort.InferenceSession(onnx_filepath, providers=providers, sess_options=sess_options)


def onnxrt_inference(ort_session, arr, device):
    upstreams_onnxrt = {  # removal of the unused inputs
        "input": ort.OrtValue.ortvalue_from_numpy(arr, device, ONNXRT_DEVICE_IDX)}

    outs = ort_session.run(
        input_feed=upstreams_onnxrt,
        output_names=OUTPUT_NAMES)
    assert len(outs) == 1
    return outs[0]


def print_result(device, is_session_shared):
    np.random.seed(42)
    session = create_onnxrt_session(ONNX_FILEPATH, device)

    is_good = True
    for seq_length in range(50):
        if not is_session_shared:
            session = create_onnxrt_session(ONNX_FILEPATH, device)
        inps = np.random.randn(seq_length, *PARTIAL_SHAPE).astype(np.float32)
        outs = onnxrt_inference(session, inps, device)
        if not np.allclose(inps, outs):

            print(f"BUG on seq_length: {seq_length}  -  max_diff: {max_diff}")
            is_good = False
            continue

    if is_good:

print("Results with SINGLE inference Session for CPU")

print("Results with SHARED inference Session for CPU")

ONNXRT_DEVICE_IDX = ONNXRT_DEVICE_CUDA_IDX

print_result("cuda", is_session_shared=True)

print("Results with SINGLE inference Session for CUDA")
```

title: Onnx runtime threading is broken in gunicorn

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

labels.name: more info needed
labels.description: issues that cannot be triaged until more information is submitted by the original user

body:
**Describe the bug**
When running onnx runtime inside `gunicorn` server two issues occur:
- setting `intra_op_num_threads` to anything other than 1 doesn't have any effect - CPU utilization doesn't go up and inference time is the same
- setting `inter_op_num_threads` >= 2 and `exec_mode=PARALLEL` causes whole server to stuck infinitely in `InferenceSession#run`.  

**System information**
- MacOS BigSur native,  ubuntu 18 docker container on MacOS BigSur and Linux Ubuntu 16.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from pypi
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.1
- Python version: 3.7.8
- Default CPU executor
- gunicorn 20.0.4

**To Reproduce**
Create `InferenceSession` inside gunicorn server with:
- `intra_ops_num_threads` > 1, run inference and observe CPU utilization stay the same, e.g. via `htop`
- `inter_ops_num_threads` > 1 and `execution_mode=PARALLEL`, run inference - it should hang the server

**Expected behavior**
I expect onnx runtime to behave exactly the same as it does without `gunicorn` (tested with the same model) or in `bjoern` server (also tested with the same model) which means: respect `intra_ops` parameter and run correctly in `parallel` mode

**Additional context**
I assume this is not bug inside onnxruntime, though I would be thankful if you could point out why onnxruntime threading doesn't work correctly on `gunicorn` server

```
import numpy as np
from sklearn.datasets import make_regression
from sklearn.gaussian_process import GaussianProcessRegressor as GPR
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

model = GPR()

#Convert to onnx and run predictions.
initial_type=[('data_in', FloatTensorType([None, X.shape[1]]))]
onx = convert_sklearn(pipe, initial_types=initial_type)
sess = rt.InferenceSession(onx.SerializeToString())
pred_ort = sess.run(None, {'data_in': vx1.astype(np.float32)})[0]

#Show output for comparison.
print(pred_ort[:10])
print(vy1[:10])
```

title: Avoid segmentation fault when creating session with TRT EP or OpenVINO EP using python
body:
When creating ort session with TRT EP or OpenVINO EP in an environment where dependencies are not installed or not in the LD_LIBRARY_PATH, in some cases, it will cause segmentation fault due to not properly handle return value. 
issue is described in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/9747

This PR fixes this issue as well as makes TRT EP follow the same pattern as CUDA EP. 
Which means when user explicitly sets TRT EP but having one of following situation:

> 1. ORT_TENSORRT_UNAVAILABLE is set to 1 by _ld_preload.py (in manylinux only)

> 2. ORT_TENSORRT_UNAVAILABLE/CUDA_PATH not being set and TRT libraries are not installed or not in the LD_LIBRARY_PATH

TRT EP will be skipped and fallback to other EPs.
